==Motivation==

Bitcoin’s security rests on the computational hardness of the elliptic curve discrete log problem (ECDLP) over secp256k1. Shor’s algorithm, running on a cryptographically relevant quantum computer (CRQC), can solve ECDLP in polynomial time, breaking both ECDSA and Schnorr signatures. The timeline for a CRQC remains uncertain, but the trend is toward shorter estimates. Whether a CRQC arrives in 2030 or 2040 (or never), Bitcoin must be prepared before it arrives; migration under duress is far riskier than proactive preparation.

===Why Hash-Based Signatures===

Among PQ signature families, hash-based schemes occupy a unique position: Their security relies solely on the security of the underlying hash function. This is, arguably, the most conservative and well-studied assumption available. In conditions where acceptance of a cryptographic signature requires a network-wide soft fork, conservatism in cryptographic assumptions is the most significant decision parameter.

One can also construct the shortest suitable Post-Quantum sig+pub schemes (among lattice-, hash-based, and multivariate schemes) using hash-based designs.

This conservative nature permits a long-term strategy of cryptographic agility for Bitcoin holders: By committing to hash-based public keys alongside keys of a more “risky” algorithm inside the leaves of a script tree, a Bitcoin user may retain the usage benefits of the risky scheme and the robust security of the hash-based scheme. This technique can hedge against cryptanalytic breakthroughs over the scale of decades.

===Why SHRINCS===

NIST-standardized SLH-DSA (the standardized version of SPHINCS+) produces a stateless signature ranging from 7856 bytes (SLH-DSA-SHA2-128s) at the 128-bit classical security level. In the Bitcoin context, where each witness byte affects the transaction fees and consumes scarce block space, these sizes are painful for routine/regular transactions. SHRINCS addresses that through a hybrid stateful+stateless design:

* Stateful mode: uses an XMSS tree where each signature consists of a single WOTS+C signature and a Merkle authentication path. Shallow-depth XMSS leaves have short authentication paths while deeper leaves have longer ones. This permits constructions with very short signatures - as small as XXX bytes (with the XMSS leaf at depth 1) - at the cost of the burden of tracking state.
* Stateless mode (fallback): uses a variant of SLH-DSA (FIPS-205) with a smaller parameter set, producing a 5776-byte signature.
* The single public key: the scheme presumes a single public key - a 48-byte structure which commits to both stateful and stateless components.

While larger than the stateful mode, a SHRINCS stateless signature is still 2 kilobytes smaller than SLH-DSA-SHA2-128s. It is used in the case the signer's state is lost, corrupted, or intentionally reset (e.g. after seed recovery). The stateless path guarantees that keys remain usable even if state is lost, at the cost of an expensive and large signature.

===Design Rationale: Unified Scheme vs. Separate Opcodes===

An alternative approach would be to redefine <code>OP_SUCCESS</code> codes specifically for SHRINCS, without changing the tap leaf version. While this was considered for a while, redefining <code>OP_CHECKSIG</code> was preferable for a number of reasons:

* New signature algorithms may need to be added in the future. With our approach of parameterizing <code>OP_CHECKSIG</code> to accept algorithm flags, new signature verification algorithms can be added by simply defining a new algorithm flag. Whereas if we were to set a precedent by redefining <code>OP_SUCCESS</code> opcodes, new sets of opcodes would need to be redefined for every new algorithm, and they would not interoperate well.
* New opcodes involving signature verification may be added in the future, such as <code>OP_CHECKSIGFROMSTACK</code> (BIP-0348), and a unified approach makes inter-BIP compatibility easier to engineer. If this BIP is deployed first, then BIP-0348 could be updated to support the new tapscript version by following the algorithm flag system defined in this BIP. Conversely, if BIP-0348 is deployed first, then this BIP could be updated to also redefine <code>OP_CHECKSIGFROMSTACK</code> in the new tap leaf version <code>0xC2</code>.

An even more segregated approach would be to deploy XMSS and SPHINCS+ as independent algorithms, so that they may be placed in separate tapscript leaves. This is a more flexible construction, which allows the user to combine spending paths as they will, but SHRINCS takes a unified approach for the following reasons:

* <b>Simpler wallet integration</b>: a single opcode with a single public key and a mode flag is easier to integrate into wallets than several independent signature algorithms, which have to be coordinated.
* <b>Multisignature complexity</b>: With SPHINCS and XMSS as separate algorithms, a threshold multisignature script must handle the combinatorial explosion of each signer potentially using their stateful or stateless key.

===Design Rationale: Hybridization===

There exist <i>signature combiners</i> such as Bird-of-Prey<ref>[https://eprint.iacr.org/2025/1844]</ref> which allow efficient hybridization of classical and post-quantum signature schemes. A hybrid scheme is at least as secure as either of the two base schemes, requiring successful attacks on both base schemes to be considered vulnerable as a whole. With a well-designed combiner, one can achieve stronger security notions than naive signature and public key concatenation. Well-designed signature combiners like BoP also reduce overall signature size compared to a naive combiner because the verifier can recover or reuse some components of the signature.<ref>[https://delvingbitcoin.org/t/bird-of-prey-2-non-malleable-schnorr-pq-signatures/2514]</ref>

In this proposal we elect <b>not</b> to introduce a dedicated hybrid signature scheme combiner for Schnorr+SHRINCS, for a few reasons:

* <b>Redundancy.</b> Deploying SHRINCS as a standalone signature scheme is desirable for efficient quantum-safe spending of bitcoin. If standalone SHRINCS is available, users will already have access to hybridization techniques by using hybrid scripts.
* <b>Lack of value.</b> Strong unforgeability - one of the main selling points of using a combiner - is not security-critical in Bitcoin because segregated witnesses don't affect TXIDs. At best a hybrid scheme would provide a minor ~5%-10% improvement in witness size over a naive scripting approach, and this is still less efficient than keeping keys compartmentalized in isolated spending paths.
* <b>Complexity & fragility.</b> A hybrid scheme would necessitate new Schnorr signing sub-algorithms, because combiners like Bird-of-Prey don't use Schnorr as a black-box. This greatly expands the scope of implementation.
* <b>Security.</b> Standalone SHRINCS uses strictly weaker cryptographic assumptions than BIP340, so adding hybridization with Schnorr hedges only against implementation flaws or state reuse in SHRINCS. Both risks can already be effectively mitigated using formal code verification and cautious wallet design.

We thus conclude that deploying a unified hybrid scheme would not offer justifiable value to Bitcoin users, and comes at the expense of great risk and effort in adding a bespoke new signature algorithm, which very few people would use because of the cheaper options available, such as placing public keys for each algorithm in isolated leaf scripts in P2MR.

Users who do find value in hedging against state reuse or implementation flaws in SHRINCS may do so using explicit multisignature scripts which verify each signature algorithm individually.


