==Specification==

===Overview===

This BIP defines a new tapscript leaf version <code>0xC2</code>, in which all signature verification opcodes, such as <code>OP_CHECKSIG</code>, <code>OP_CHECKSIGADD</code>, <code>OP_CHECKSIGVERIFY</code>, etc, are redefined to support multiple signature schemes. The exact verification algorithm to use is dictated at evaluation time, via a 1-byte algorithm flag prefix on the public key arguments.

* <code>OP_CHECKSIG</code>: Pop two elements from the stack: a pubkey, followed by a signature. Fail the script if the pubkey is empty. Pop a 1-byte signature algorithm flag from the pubkey. Verify the signature against the public key using the designated algorithm. Verification is presumed successful for any unrecognized algorithm flag. Push the result: <code>1</code> on success, the empty vector on an empty signature, and fail the script if signature verification fails.

* <code>OP_CHECKSIGVERIFY</code>: Pop two elements from the stack: a pubkey, followed by a signature. Fail the script if the pubkey is empty. Pop a 1-byte signature algorithm flag from the pubkey. Verify the signature against the public key using the designated algorithm. Verification is presumed successful for any unrecognized algorithm flag. Fail the script if signature validation fails, or if the signature is empty.

* <code>OP_CHECKSIGADD</code>: Pop three elements from the stack: a pubkey, followed by a CScriptNum <code>n</code>, followed by a signature. Fail the script if the pubkey is empty or if the CScriptNum is larger than 4 bytes. Pop a 1-byte signature algorithm flag from the pubkey. Verify the signature against the public key using the designated algorithm. Verification is presumed successful for any unrecognized algorithm flag. Push the result: <code>n</code> if the signature is empty, or <code>n+1</code> if the signature is valid. Fail the script if signature verification fails.

Threshold (m-of-n) and multi (n-of-n) signatures are realized by combining <code>OP_CHECKSIGADD</code> with existing arithmetic <code>OP_ADD</code> and <code>OP_NUMEQUAL</code> opcodes, following the same pattern used in BIP342. Since each pubkey commits to its own algorithm, a multisignature script may consist of multiple keys using disjoint verification algorithms, and each signer need not care which algorithm their peers use.

In all other aspects, tapscript version <code>0xC2</code> is identical to the original tapscript version <code>0xC0</code> defined in BIP342.

