===Public Key Format===

When CHECKSIG opcodes pop a non-empty pubkey from the stack, the verifier assumes the pubkey byte vector has the following structure:

<pre>
flag || pubkey
</pre>

… where <code>flag</code> is a byte corresponding to a standardized signature verification algorithm flag.

Two verification algorithm flags are defined in this BIP:

* <code>0x01</code>: SHRINCS.
* <code>0x02</code>: BIP340<ref>By using <code>0x02</code> as the algorithm flag for a BIP340 pubkey, the key appears the same as it would if we took the full lifted secp256k1 curve point and encoded it with the standard compressed point encoding format.</ref>.

Any pubkey which uses an unidentified algorithm flag prefix is essentially an “anyone-can-spend” public key, because verifiers will auto-succeed when they validate signatures against that key. This allows future BIPs to define new verification algorithms using a soft-fork.

We now define the signature verification algorithms for these two flags.


===SHRINCS===

A SHRINCS public key is a 48-byte string constructed as:
<pre>
PK = PK.seed || PK.sf_root || PK.sl_root
</pre>

* <code>PK.seed</code> is a domain separator, used in all hash operations while producing the signature.
* <code>PK.sf_root</code> is a root commitment to a stateful XMSS public key.
* <code>PK.sl_root</code> is a root commitment to a stateless SPHINCS public key.


====Signature Format====

SHRINCS signatures can exceed the 520-byte limit for stack elements. Therefore, the new tapscript version <code>0xC2</code> introduced in this BIP lifts the 520 byte limit on stack element sizes to 6000 bytes.

SHRINCS signatures may either use the stateful or the stateless path inside the key, and either is equally valid. Stateless SHRINCS signatures are very large, but always a constant size of 5776 bytes. Stateful SHRINCS signatures are much shorter, but are of variable size, to a maximum of XXX bytes.


====Stateful Signature Layout====

A SHRINCS stateful signature consists of

- An XMSS node address
- A 16-byte randomizer
- A WOTS+C signature
- A merkle authentication path

Unlike P2MR and P2TR script trees, XMSS requires explicit left/right direction in the structure of its merkle tree for security.<ref>Can we still prove XMSS secure if we use an unstructured (directionless) tree, a la taproot? (better privacy and XMSS clients are more flexible) No. Unstructured XMSS trees would give an attacker an advantage in multi-target attacks. Say you have an XMSS tree with height two (i.e. four leaves). Let’s say you reveal the two intermediate nodes in the first layer to an attacker, e.g. by signing a transaction. The hash function used to compute both of these nodes must be the same - otherwise it would not be a directionless tree - So the attacker can try preimage search on both hash function outputs at once. This doubles their chances of successfully finding a preimage. Scaled up, with more target hashes, the attacker increases their advantage even more.</ref> The XMSS node address is necessary for the verifier to be able to correctly follow the Merkle authentication path back to the <code>PK.sf_root</code> hash.

We use a node address encoding of 9 bytes: 1 byte for the node depth, and 8 bytes for the node index. This allows the signer to specify any position in the XMSS tree, to a maximum depth of 255, and a maximum index within a layer of 2<sup>64</sup> - 1. This permits both balanced and unbalanced XMSS constructions, or a combination thereof. For guaranteed security we recommend using only balanced or unbalanced trees.

TODO: should we use a variable-size encoding for the node index in the serialized signature? Seems like 99% of use-cases will have a very low index, so we have a lot of ways to optimize here.

* Unbalanced XMSS is where the XMSS tree is "leaned over" to one side. Each node has a WOTS leaf and a child branch which also has one leaf and a child, and so on. The number of WOTS leaves is the depth of the tree plus 1.
** Very small signatures initially, but signature size increases with repeated use.
** Key generation and signing are very fast.
** Ideal for use-cases where very few signatures per keypair are needed, e.g. On-chain Bitcoin wallets that avoid reusing addresses.
* Balanced XMSS is where the branches of the XMSS tree are perfectly balanced, with some power-of-two number of WOTS leaves all at the same depth.
** Small, constant-size signatures. Not as small as unbalanced XMSS.
** Key generation becomes very performance-intensive for deeper trees.
** Signing is fast if sufficient memory is available to cache the leaves of the XMSS tree.
** Ideal for use-cases where large numbers of constant-size compact signatures must be made quickly, from the same keypair.

The SHRINCS stateful verifier does not distinguish between balanced or unbalanced XMSS. The verifier cannot distinguish the shape of the signer's XMSS tree beyond what is implied by the presence of WOTS leaves at the node addresses specified in published signatures.

