==Backward Compatibility==

Existing script semantics in P2WSH and other legacy address formats is unaffected. This BIP only affects P2TR and P2MR tapscript that are using leaf version <code>0xC2</code>.

==Security==

The basic script validation rules of the new tapsript version <code>0xC2</code> are mostly inherited from BIP342. The only novel addition is the algorithm flag parsed by the CHECKSIG family of opcodes, so we will focus on that.

The algorithm flag is adjoined as part of the pubkey in this design. Pubkeys are typically committed as part of locking scripts, and so an attacker will usually not be able to control which algorithm will be used by the verifier. This rules out any “rollback” attacks where an adversary could trick a verifier into using the wrong algorithm - e.g. to interpret a SHRINCS public key as a BIP340 key, or vice versa. This design also makes the security argument easier: To modify the signature algorithm, you must be able to modify the pubkey that a user commits coins to, and if you can modify a pubkey that a user commits coins to, you can already forge signatures and steal coins. Though, in a possible future where OP_CAT or OP_SLICE are re-enabled, poorly-written scripts could be manipulated and future developers will need to bear this risk in mind when designing protocols.

For forwards-compatibility, reserved algorithm flags are left as auto-success paths, which could be a security risk if wallets misuse them. This should not affect any wallet that uses standardized algorithms to generate public keys. Selecting the correct algorithm flag for your keypair is straightforward and easy to validate by inspecting scripts visually.

This BIP specifies two signature algorithm flags: BIP340 and SHRINCS. The BIP340 signature algorithm is already a well-studied secure signature protocol, so we leave discussion of its security to BIP340, and focus instead on the novel hash-based cryptosystem SHRINCS, introduced in this BIP.

The SHRINCS verification algorithm consists mostly of evaluating a series of hash functions on the signature to recompute a certain hash. Ultimately the verifier recomputes one of the SHRINCS public key components: <code>PK.sf_root</code> or <code>PK.sl_root</code>.

The security of SHRINCS relies solely on the security of the underlying hash function, which seems very robust in general. Given a hash function with output width of <code>b</code> bits (given a big enough internal state), the best-known classical attack is simple trial-and-error, which yields a second preimage after 2<sup>b</sup> tries on average. The best case quantum attack using Grover’s algorithm yields a second preimage in time on the order of O(2<sup>b/2</sup>). In other words, using a <code>b</code>-bit hash gives <code>b</code> bits of classical security, and <code>b/2</code> bits of quantum security.

While the definition of quantum security bits is less clear, the classical analogue is well-studied. The elliptic curve discrete log problem, which BIP340 relies upon, can be solved classically in time O(sqrt(n)), where <code>n</code> is the order of the curve. The secp256k1 curve order is an approximately 2<sup>256</sup> bit number, thus the BIP340 algorithm has around 256/2 = 128 bits of classical security against forgery and key recovery.

Having no concrete basis on which to select a level of quantum security against Grover’s algorithm, we aim for SHRINCS to match BIP340’s level of classical security, and so follow the NIST-I security level guidelines: 128 bits of classical security, and 64 bits of quantum security. We do so by using a 128-bit truncation of the SHA256 hash function to instantiate SHRINCS, and this mirrors the NIST FIPS-205 specification’s reasoning for their SLH-DSA-SHA2-128 hash-based parameter sets.<ref>Readers may wonder why we can use 128-bit hash functions safely here, when the rest of Bitcoin depends on 256-bit hashes. This is because most of the usage of hash functions in Bitcoin depends on collision resistance for security, and collisions in a <code>b</code>-bit hash function can be found in only 2<sup>b/2</sup> attempts classically, due to the birthday “paradox”. In SHRINCS we do not need collision resistance, so we can get away with much smaller hash functions.</ref> We use SHA256 because it is already part of Bitcoin consensus, because hardware optimization techniques are readily available, and because if collision resistance of SHA256 is broken, then many other features of Bitcoin will also be compromised anyway.

